# =============================================================================
# slash — example rc file
# =============================================================================
#
# Copy or symlink this to `~/.slashrc` (or whichever path your slash
# is configured to source) and uncomment the lines you want active.
# Slash sources this file on every interactive session start.
#
# NOTHING in this file is required for slash to work. Out of the
# box you get:
#
#   - prefix-aware Up/Down history navigation
#   - autosuggestions (dim ghost text from history)
#   - Tab completion (commands, paths, git subcommands, etc.)
#   - reverse-i-search via Ctrl-R
#   - Alt-P / Alt-N as emacs-style history-prev/next aliases
#   - all the standard emacs editing keys (Ctrl-A, Ctrl-E, Alt-B, ...)
#
# This file shows the patterns most users want on top of that.


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Prompt
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# `$SLASH_PROMPT` picks a preset (default / rich / minimal). `$PROMPT`
# (zsh-style format string) overrides the preset entirely — drop in
# any zsh PROMPT and it just works.

# export SLASH_PROMPT=rich

# Steel-blue powerline-ish prompt with HH:MM:SS, user@host, cwd:
# export PROMPT='%F{#ecede8}%K{#43669d}%D{%H:%M:%S} %F{#43669d}%K{#81a1c7}%F{#ecede8} %n@%m %F{#81a1c7}%K{}%F{#ecede8}%k %~> %f'


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Syntax highlighting theme
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# `$SLASH_THEME` picks one of four built-in palettes. Colors come
# directly from the canonical sources (GitHub Primer / VS Code defaults).
#
#   github-dark    Default for dark terminals (the prettylights palette
#                  used by github.com itself and the GitHub VS Code theme)
#   github-light   Matched pair, designed for white backgrounds
#   vscode-dark    VS Code Dark+ (Microsoft's default since 2015)
#   vscode-light   VS Code Light+
#
# Convenience aliases: `github` and `vscode` auto-pick the dark/light
# variant from your terminal background. `dark` / `light` alias the
# GitHub variants.
#
# When unset, Slash auto-detects via `$COLORFGBG` and defaults to the
# GitHub family.

# export SLASH_THEME=github-dark


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Notifications
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# `$SLASH_NOTIFY=immediate` mirrors bash `set -b`: backgrounded
# jobs print their `[N] Done <cmd>` line ABOVE the in-progress
# prompt buffer the moment they finish, instead of waiting for
# the next Enter. Leave unset for default (between-prompts).

# export SLASH_NOTIFY=immediate


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Abbreviations — typed-name shortcuts (see `str -h` and PLAN §12)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# `str NAME { body }` defines an editor-time literal-text rewrite.
# Type `NAME` followed by Space or Enter; the visible buffer is
# rewritten in place. Pure text → text; no expansion, no code.

# str ..   { cd .. }
# str ...  { cd ../.. }
# str .... { cd ../../.. }
# str -    { cd - }
# str ll   { ls -la }
# str gst  { git status }
# str gl   { git log --oneline -20 }


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Key bindings — modifier-key shortcuts (see `key --actions`, `key --probe`)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# Two forms:
#
#   key KEYSPEC bare-ident       # bind to a named editor action
#   key KEYSPEC "literal text"   # type bytes; trailing \n = also accept
#
# KEYSPEC: Ctrl-X / Esc-X (or Alt-X / Meta-X / Option-X / Opt-X —
# all five spell the same meta-modified chord), Ctrl-Esc-Right,
# Shift-F7, etc. Slash prints the canonical form as `Esc-X` because
# that's wire-honest: terminals emit a literal `\e` (Escape) byte
# prefix on the next keystroke, regardless of platform or which
# physical modifier the user pressed.
#
# `key --actions` lists every registered action. `key --probe` opens
# an interactive diagnostic — press any key and slash names it +
# shows the raw bytes.
#
# macOS:
#
#   - To fire `Esc-X` chords with one keystroke (Option+X), enable
#     "Use Option as Meta key" in Terminal.app Preferences → Profiles
#     → Keyboard, or in iTerm2 set the Left/Right Option key to
#     "Esc+". With this setting, Option+L sends `\e L` bytes → fires
#     `key Esc-L "..."`.
#
#   - With the toggle OFF (the default), Option+letter emits a
#     Unicode compose character (Option+L → `¬`, Option+P → `π`,
#     etc.) which slash receives as a literal codepoint, NOT a
#     meta chord. You can bind directly to those codepoints if you
#     want to: `key "¬" "ls -la\n"`. But the cleaner mental model
#     is to keep the compose chars as data (so you can type π if
#     you want to type π) and use `Esc-X` for chords.
#
#   - The two-keystroke `Esc-X` form (press Escape, then X within
#     ~500ms) works identically on every terminal regardless of
#     preferences. This is the recommended path if you don't want
#     to change terminal settings.

# History navigation (these are seeded as defaults — listed here
# so you know they exist):
# key Esc-P history-prev-prefix       # match history backward by prefix
# key Esc-N history-next-prefix       # match history forward by prefix

# Universal shortcuts (uncomment any you'd actually use):
# key Esc-L "ls -la\n"                # list current dir
# key Esc-G "git status\n"            # git status
# key Esc-D "cd ~/Code\n"             # jump to your code dir
# key Esc-H "cd ~\n"                  # go home

# Pipe whatever's on the prompt into less:
# key Esc-\\ " | less\n"

# A "comment this line, save for later" pattern (push current line
# into history with a # in front, so it's recallable with Up + edit):
# key Esc-# "#\n"


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Traps
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# `trap 'cmd' EXIT` runs the command when the shell exits.

# trap 'echo "see ya"' EXIT


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Command-not-found rescue hook
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# If you define `cmd command_not_found { ... }`, slash invokes it
# whenever a typed command can't be resolved (no builtin, no `cmd`
# definition, no executable on $PATH). The handler sees:
#
#   $0  = "command_not_found"
#   $1  = the original (missing) command name
#   $2..$N = the original arguments
#
# The handler's exit status becomes the failed command's exit
# status — so `return 0` makes the original invocation look like a
# success, while `return 127` (or any non-zero) preserves the
# original semantics.
#
# Re-entry is guarded: a missing command invoked from inside the
# handler will NOT re-invoke the handler. Slash falls back to the
# standard `slash: command not found: NAME` message in that case.
# Matches zsh's `command_not_found_handler` convention.

# cmd command_not_found
#   echo "slash: '$1' not installed; try `brew install $1` or `apt install $1`"
#   return 127
